Simulation Study

Simulation 1

We consider the linear model based on the vector

\[ \begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\beta}^T &= [1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{58} , 1], &\text{(Case 1)}\\ \boldsymbol{\beta}^T &= [1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{58} , 1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{100}], &\text{(Case 2)} \end{aligned} \]

and the following

  • \(\sigma^2 = 1\)
  • The covariates are standard normal realizations with pairwise correlation given by \(corr(x_j, x_k) = 0.5^{|j-k|}\)
  • \(n = 80\) and \(n^\ast = 800\)
  • \(B = 500\) (Monte-Carlo replications)

Case 1: \(n > p\)

simu1_part1 <- run_simulation(nb_simu = 500, true_beta = c(1, rep(0,58), 1),
                              n = 80, n_star = 800, sigma = 1, cor_X = 0.5,
                              xlim = c(1.035, 1.09), ylim = c(2.35, 5.2),
                              xlab = expression(PE[y]), 
                              ylab = "Mean(#sel.)",
                              title = "Simulation 1: n > p",
                              adaptive = FALSE)  

kable(simu1_part1)

Simulation 2

We consider the linear model based on the vector

\[ \begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\beta}^T &= [2, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{16}, \underbrace{0.1, \ldots, 0.1}_\text{6}, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{16}, 2, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1], &\text{(Case 1)}\\ \boldsymbol{\beta}^T &= [2, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{16}, \underbrace{0.1, \ldots, 0.1}_\text{6}, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{16}, 2, 0, 1, 2, 0, 1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{100}], &\text{(Case 2)} \end{aligned} \]

and the following

  • \(\sigma^2 = 2\)
  • The covariates are standard normal realizations with pairwise correlation given by \(corr(x_j, x_k) = 0.5^{|j-k|}\)
  • \(n = 100\) and \(n^\ast = 1000\)
  • \(B = 500\) (Monte-Carlo replications)

Case 1: \(n > p\)

beta <- c(rep(c(2, 0, 1), 2),rep(0, 16),rep(0.1, 6),rep(0, 16),rep(c(2, 0, 1), 2))
simu2_part1 <- run_simulation(nb_simu = 500, true_beta = beta,
                              n = 100, n_star = 1000, sigma = 2, cor_X = 0.5,
                              xlim = c(4.73, 5.4), ylim = c(7.5, 16),
                              xlab = expression(PE[y]),
                              ylab = "Mean(#sel.)", 
                              title = "Simulation 2: n > p",
                              adaptive = FALSE)

Simulation 3

We consider the linear model based on the vector

\[ \begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\beta}^T &= [3, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{5}, 1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{10}, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{10}, 2, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{20}], &\text{(Case 1)}\\ \boldsymbol{\beta}^T &= [3, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{5}, 1, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{10}, 0.05, 0.05, 0.05, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{10}, 2, \underbrace{0, \ldots, 0}_\text{120}], &\text{(Case 2)} \end{aligned} \]

and the following

  • \(\sigma^2 = 3\)
  • The covariates are standard normal realizations with pairwise correlation given by \(corr(x_j, x_k) = 0.25^{|j-k|}\)
  • \(n = 100\) and \(n^\ast = 1000\)
  • \(B = 500\) (Monte-Carlo replications)

Case 1: \(n > p\)

beta <- c(3,rep(0,5),1,rep(0,10),rep(0.05,3),rep(0,10),2,rep(0,20))
simu3_part1 <- run_simulation(nb_simu = 500, true_beta = beta,
                              n = 100, n_star = 1000, sigma = 3, cor_X = 0.25,
                              xlim = c(9.65, 10.5), ylim = c(3, 11.5),
                              xlab = expression(PE[y]), 
                              ylab = "Mean(#sel.)", 
                              title = "Simulation 3: n > p",
                              adaptive = FALSE)
